MAINTENANCE AGREEMENT
This Maintenance Agreement (the Agreement) is entered into as of November 30, 2022 between Bellflower Solar 1, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (Bellflower), and AEP Indiana Michigan Transmission Company, Inc., an Indiana corporation (AEPIMTC). For purposes of this Agreement, AEPIMTC and Bellflower shall each be referred to as a Party and collectively as the Parties.
RECITALS
A. PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. (PJM), Bellflower, and AEPIMTC are parties to that certain Interconnection Service Agreement, PJM Queue AE2-297, Original Service Agreement No. 6312, accepted by the FERC on April 22, 2022 in Docket Nos. ER22-847-000, et al., effective as of December 21, 2021 (ISA), and that certain Interconnection Construction Service Agreement, PJM Queue AE2-297, Original Service Agreement No. 6313, effective as of December 21, 2021 (ICSA). B. Pursuant to the ISA and ICSA, Generator elected the option to construct certain Interconnected Transmission Owner Attachment Facilities and Direct Connection Network Upgrades described in Schedules D and I of ICSA (collectively, the Station). C. Contemporaneous with the execution of this Agreement, Bellflower is transferring operational control of the Station to PJM and AEPIMTC. Subsequently, Bellflower and AEPIMTC intend to have Bellflower transfer ownership of the Station to AEPIMTC. D. Bellflower desires to have AEPIMTC perform certain maintenance activities for the Station until the closing of transfer of ownership of the Station from Bellflower to AEPIMTC (Closing), and AEPIMTC is willing to perform such maintenance activities upon the terms and conditions set forth in this Agreement.
AGREEMENTS
NOW, THEREFORE, the Parties hereby agree as follows:
1. DEFINITIONS; RULES OF CONSTRUCTION 1.1. Definitions. As used in this Agreement, terms defined in Exhibit A have the meanings set forth therein. 1.2. Rules of Construction. Unless the context of this Agreement requires otherwise, the plural includes the singular, and the singular includes the plural. The words include, includes and including are not limiting and have the inclusive meaning of including without limitation. The words hereof, herein, hereby, hereunder and other similar terms of this Agreement refer to this Agreement as a whole and not exclusively to any particular provision of this Agreement. All pronouns and any variations thereof will be deemed to refer to masculine, feminine, or neuter, singular, or plural, as the identity of the Person or Persons may require. Unless otherwise expressly 1
provided, any agreement, instrument, or Applicable Law defined or referred to herein means such agreement or instrument or Applicable Law as from time to time amended, modified, or supplemented, including (in the case of agreements or instruments) by waiver or consent and (in the case of Applicable Law) by succession of comparable successor law and includes (in the case of agreements or instruments) references to all attachments thereto and instruments incorporated therein. A reference to a Party includes its successors and permitted assigns. This Agreement is the result of negotiations between, and has been reviewed by, the Parties, and their respective counsel have had the opportunity to review this Agreement. Accordingly, this Agreement will be deemed to be the product of all Parties hereto, and no ambiguity will be construed in favor of or against any Party. 2. TERM AND TERMINATION 2.1. Effective Date. AEPIMTC shall file this Agreement with FERC, and Bellflower agrees to cooperate with AEPIMTC and provide reasonable assistance to AEPIMTC in such filing and proceedings related thereto. This Agreement shall become effective on the date deemed effective by FERC (Effective Date). However, if FERC or any reviewing court, in such order or in any separate order, suspends this Agreement or any part thereof, institutes an investigation or proceeding under the provisions of the Federal Power Act with respect to the justness and reasonableness of the provisions of this Agreement or any other agreement referred to or contemplated by this Agreement, or imposes any conditions, limitation or qualifications under any of the provisions of the Federal Power Act that individually or in the aggregate are determined by AEPIMTC or Bellflower to be adverse to it, then either AEPIMTC or Bellflower may terminate this Agreement upon written notice to the other Party. Alternatively, the Parties can agree that this Agreement should remain in effect, with each Party retaining its rights to address any relevant order, including seeking to negotiate with the other Party an amendment to this Agreement. 2.2. Term. Subject to termination pursuant to Section 2.3, the term of this Agreement shall commence as of the Effective Date and shall continue until the Closing (Term). 2.3. Events of Termination. This Agreement may be terminated by the Parties as follows: 2.3.1. Either Party may terminate this Agreement for an Event of Default as provided in Section 5.2. 2.3.2. This Agreement may be terminated by mutual written agreement of the Parties. 2.3.3. Either Party may terminate this Agreement in accordance with Section 2.1. 2.4. Regulatory Approval of Termination. No termination hereunder shall become effective until the terminating Party (or the Parties jointly) tenders to FERC any required notification of termination of this Agreement and obtains acceptance thereof by FERC as may be required. The FERC order accepting such termination will establish the effective date of the termination of this Agreement. 2
3. SERVICES 3.1. Services. 3.1.1. General Scope. Subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, AEPIMTC will perform routine inspections of the Station facilities; on-site switching and tagging; preventive equipment maintenance; repair and replace worn or defective facilities as reasonably determined necessary by AEPIMTC, subject to Section 3.1.2; perform vegetation control on the Station premises described and depicted on Exhibit C attached hereto (the Premises) and such other maintenance activities as AEPIMTC deems reasonably necessary and appropriate, subject to the limitations set forth in this Section 3.1 (collectively, the Services). AEPIMTC shall provide the personnel, tools and equipment that AEPIMTC deems necessary or advisable in connection with the Services. AEPIMTC shall perform the routine inspection and preventive equipment maintenance activities at such frequency and using such practices as it would utilize for similar maintenance activities for similar AEPIMTC facilities. 3.1.2. Major Repairs or Replacement; Removal. If AEPIMTC determines that a necessary repair or replacement will exceed $10,000.00 (in either case, a Major Repair or Replacement), AEPIMTC will notify Bellflower and will not perform such Service unless mutually agreed by AEPIMTC and Bellflower except in the case of an Emergency (as defined in Section 3.1.4). Unless otherwise mutually agreed by the Parties, Bellflower shall procure any necessary materials and equipment for any Major Repair or Replacement. If Bellflower does not provide its agreement for AEPIMTC to undertake such Major Repair or Replacement, AEPIMTC not have any liability under this Agreement and shall be indemnified by Bellflower pursuant to Article 9 for all damages arising out of or in connection with the failure to undertake such Major Repair or Replacement. Only Bellflower may determine whether any of the Station facilities may be retired, and except in an Emergency, AEPIMTC shall not remove any Station facilities without the prior written approval of Bellflower. 3.1.3. Warranties. Except in the event of an Emergency, AEPIMTC shall notify Bellflower prior to repair or replacement of defective equipment such that Bellflower may pursue warranties from its contractors and subcontractors. 3.1.4. Emergencies. Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement, if AEPIMTC believes in good faith that a condition or circumstance that threatens imminent harm to Persons, property, the environment or the electric system exists or has occurred or that the performance of any of the Services would (in the reasonable judgment of AEPIMTC) create an unreasonable safety risk to Persons, property or the environment, or would violate the safety and reliability policies or procedures of AEPIMTC or any AEPIMTC Resources (each of the foregoing, an Emergency), AEPIMTC may take such actions, or will cause such actions to be taken, that in AEPIMTCs sole 3
judgment, are reasonably required to avoid or mitigate the Emergency without the need for prior notice to or approval by Bellflower; provided, however, that AEPIMTC shall promptly notify Bellflower after such actions are taken. If AEPIMTC fails to take action, or to cause action to be taken, in response to an Emergency, Bellflower may, upon notice to AEPIMTC, take action, or cause action to be taken, to address the Emergency. 3.1.5. Scope Limitation. Bellflower agrees that the following activities are not covered within the scope of the Services: (a) maintenance of Bellflowers generation facilities, including relays; (b) maintenance of the transmission line from the generation facility to the Point of Interconnection, including the fiber on that portion of the line; (c) capital improvements on the Station (as opposed to repair or replacement of equipment); (d) maintenance of grounds (including vegetation management) outside the Premises; (e) compliance with, or performance under, Storm Water Pollution Prevention Plans; and (f) identification, reporting, spill response or other compliance obligations associated with hazardous substances under any applicable environmental permit; provided, however, that, during performance of the Services, if AEPIMTC encounters any hazardous substances on or around the Premises, AEPIMTC shall promptly notify Bellflower and suspend performance of Services at the applicable site until such hazardous substances are removed or abated. 3.1.6. Changes to Scope. The Parties may amend the scope of the Services pursuant to an amendment of this Agreement under Section 11.3. 3.2. Standards of Performance. AEPIMTC shall perform the Services in accordance with Good Utility Practice and Applicable Law. 3.3. Use of Resources. AEPIMTC may perform the Services under this Agreement by using subcontractors, suppliers, and consultants, and personnel from its Affiliates (collectively, the AEPIMTC Resources). AEPIMTC will be solely responsible for the supervision, direction, and control of all AEPIMTC Resources engaged in the performance of the Services and such personnel will be employees or independent contractors of AEPIMTC and not of Bellflower. AEPIMTC will have the right to remove, reassign, or take any other employment-related action regarding any of the AEPIMTC Resources. AEPIMTC shall cause each AEPIMTC Resource performing the Services under this Agreement to comply with the terms and conditions of this 4
Agreement, but only AEPIMTC shall be liable under this Agreement for the performance of the obligations under this Agreement regardless of AEPIMTCs reliance on AEPIMTC Resources. 3.4. Access. Bellflower grants AEPIMTC and the AEPIMTC Resources access rights to the Station at all times during the Term as may be reasonably necessary or convenient to AEPIMTC to perform the Services. 3.5. Owner Instructions. At any time, AEPIMTC may, if it reasonably deems it to be reasonably necessary or appropriate, request and receive detailed instructions (or clarifications of directives) from Bellflower prior to taking any action with respect to the Services. AEPIMTC may defer action pending the receipt of such written instructions. Bellflower agrees that it will not unreasonably withhold or delay any instruction or direction to AEPIMTC that is necessary to enable AEPIMTC to provide the Services. 3.6. Compliance with Reliability Standards. AEPIMTC will be responsible for the maintenance of the Station, including performing all tasks and preparing and retaining all records/documentation required to comply with applicable Reliability Standards. Bellflower accepts that the Station will be maintained by AEPIMTC in accordance with the AEPIMTC maintenance and compliance practices applicable to similar facilities. The Parties acknowledge that Bellflower intends to obtain an Open Access Transmission Tariff waiver with respect to its ownership of the Station and that AEPIMTC will not register as transmission owner, transmission operator, transmission planner, or any other applicable function with respect to the Station. AEPIMTC is not required to make any filings with NERC or any other Governmental Authority on behalf of Bellflower with respect to the Station, but AEPIMTC shall provide Bellflower, at Bellflowers expense, such records, information and documents reasonably necessary for Bellflower to demonstrate compliance with applicable Reliability Standards in connection with the Station and the Services. 3.7. Responsibility for Non-Compliance. AEPIMTC shall be responsible for any penalty or fine associated with non-compliance with the applicable Reliability Standards imposed as a result of a self-report, or a Governmental Authority audit, investigation, or proceeding related to the Station or the Services, to the extent caused by AEPIMTCs gross negligence or willful misconduct in the performance of the Services. For the avoidance of doubt, any penalty or fine associated with non-compliance with any applicable Reliability Standards imposed as a result of a self-report, or a Governmental Authority audit, investigation, or proceeding related to the Station or the Services not caused by AEPIMTCs gross negligence or willful misconduct shall not be AEPIMTCs responsibility. 4. COSTS; INVOICING; TAXES 4.1. Responsibility for Costs. 4.1.1. Bellflower agrees to reimburse AEPIMTC for its costs to perform the Services. AEPIMTCs costs for the Services under this Agreement will 5
include all costs, charges, and expenses reasonably incurred by AEPIMTC in connection with the Services, including the costs of materials, equipment, and supplies from third parties, the costs of materials and equipment withdrawn from AEPIMTCs internal inventories (or those of its Affiliates), transportation and storage costs, internal payroll and payroll loading factors, travel expenses, overhead factors, other internal costs, third party expenses, sales and use taxes, and fees and costs for Governmental Approvals. AEPIMTCs costs shall be determined in a manner consistent with the formula set forth in Exhibit B. 4.1.2. Without limiting any rights it may have against third parties, Bellflower will be responsible for all capital costs associated with the Station, including replacement of failed major components. 4.1.3. All costs reasonably incurred for all actions taken by AEPIMTC to avoid or mitigate an Emergency in accordance with Section 3.1.4 will be paid or reimbursed by Bellflower. 4.2. Information Concerning Costs. On reasonable advance written notice, Bellflower will have the right to examine the pertinent records of AEPIMTC as reasonably necessary to verify that costs invoiced pursuant to this Agreement were incurred in accordance with this Agreement. Any such examination will be conducted during regular business hours at the AEPIMTC offices and shall be conducted in a manner that does not unreasonably interfere with AEPIMTCs business or operations. Bellflower will not have the right to examine the records pertaining to an invoice unless written notice of the examination is given within twenty-four (24) months after the date of such invoice. AEPIMTC shall not be obligated to provide Bellflower with access or any other rights to information to the extent such information is: (a) otherwise restricted from disclosure by AEPIMTC; or (b) privileged (e.g., pursuant to attorney-client privilege or work- product protection). Information obtained by Bellflower from AEPIMTC pursuant to this section will be considered AEPIMTCs Confidential Information pursuant to Article 9.3 regardless of whether such information is identified as confidential. 4.3. Invoices. 4.3.1. Not later than thirty (30) Calendar Days after the end of each month, AEPIMTC will deliver to Bellflower a monthly invoice which will show the charges payable by Bellflower for the month and payment will be made by Bellflower no later than thirty (30) Calendar Days after the date the invoice is received by Bellflower. 4.3.2. If Bellflower disputes any portion of any amount specified in an invoice delivered by AEPIMTC, Bellflower will pay the total amount of the invoice when due, and Bellflower shall identify the disputed amount and state the basis for disputing part of the invoice amount. If it is determined that an overpayment or underpayment has been made by Bellflower or the amount charged on an invoice is incorrect, then: (a) in the case of any overpayment by Bellflower, AEPIMTC will promptly return the amount of the 6
overpayment (or credit the amount of the overpayment on the next invoice) to Bellflower; or (b) in the case of an underpayment by Bellflower, Bellflower will promptly pay the amount of the underpayment to AEPIMTC. In each case, payment will be made together with interest at the Default Rate for the period from the date of overpayment or underpayment, until such amount has been paid or credited against a future invoice. 4.4. Tax Treatment of Costs. The amounts Bellflower agrees to pay AEPIMTC pursuant to Section 4.1 of this Agreement are exclusive of any state or local sales or use tax, or any other tax or similar charge. If AEPIMTC is required by Applicable Law to pay or collect any such tax, or if Bellflower is required to withhold such tax, then such amount will be paid or reimbursed to AEPIMTC by Bellflower. Bellflower shall not be responsible to pay any federal, state or local tax imposed on AEPIMTC and related to AEPIMTCs receipt of monies under this Agreement. 5. DEFAULT; REMEDIES 5.1. Events of Default. An Event of Default will exist: 5.1.1. As to a Party, if that Party fails to promptly pay any amount due under this Agreement within ten (10) Calendar Days following written notice of delinquency describing such failure in reasonable detail; or 5.1.2. As to a Party, if that Party fails to commence the cure of its breach of any other obligation under this Agreement within thirty (30) Calendar Days following written notification of such breach in reasonable detail; provided that if such failure is not capable of being cured within such thirty (30) Calendar Day period despite diligent efforts, then such thirty (30) Calendar Day period will be extended for such period as may be reasonably necessary to complete such cure with diligent efforts if the defaulting Party commences its cure within the initial thirty (30) Calendar Day period and thereafter prosecutes its cure diligently to completion. 5.1.3. A Party files a voluntary petition of bankruptcy or is adjudged bankrupt or insolvent, or has entered against it an order for relief, in any bankruptcy or insolvency proceeding. 5.2. Termination. If an Event of Default occurs as to a Party described in Sections 5.1.1 or 5.1.2, then the other Party will have the right to terminate the Services by written notice to the defaulting Party. Upon an Event of Default by a Party described in Section 5.1.3, the other Party may terminate this Agreement by written notice to the defaulting Party, subject to Section 2.4. 5.3. Other remedies. 5.3.1. If an Event of Default occurs and while it persists with respect to a Party, the other Party may suspend performance of its obligations with respect to the Services under this Agreement (other than its obligations to pay money for 7
Services provided) without prejudice to any other remedy that it may have under this Agreement or Applicable Law. 5.3.2. Whether or not a Party suspends performance of its obligations under, or terminates, this Agreement as a result of an Event of Default, Bellflower will pay all amounts due, if any, for Services provided prior to the date of such suspension or termination and both parties shall remain responsible for paying all indemnification obligations pursuant to Article 9. 5.3.3. Subject to the limitations in Article 8 and the indemnification obligations of Article 9: (a) either Party will be entitled to recover direct contract damages from the other Party as a result of an Event of Default (Allowable Damages). 6. FORCE MAJEURE 6.1. Effect of Force Majeure. In the event that any Party is rendered unable by reason of an event of Force Majeure occurring or arising without the fault or negligence of such Party, to perform, wholly or in part, any obligation or commitment set forth in this Agreement, then the obligations of such Party (except for the obligation to pay sums of money owing hereunder for periods prior to the event of Force Majeure) shall be suspended to the extent of such Force Majeure condition, and such Party shall not be deemed to be in default of this Agreement, for the period of such Force Majeure condition. The non-performing Party shall exercise commercially reasonable efforts to rectify the conditions brought about by the Force Majeure and to avoid or minimize delay. 6.2. Notification. In the event of the occurrence of an event of Force Majeure which prevents a Party from performing its obligations hereunder, the affected Party shall promptly notify the other Party of such Force Majeure after the determination that event of Force Majeure has occurred. 6.3. Labor Disputes. Neither Party will be required by this Agreement to settle any strike, walkout, lockout, or other labor dispute on terms which, in the sole judgment of the Party involved in the dispute, are contrary to its interest, it being understood that the settlement of strikes, walkouts, lockouts, or other labor disputes will be at the sole discretion of the Party having the difficulty. 7. DISCLAIMER OF WARRANTIES SUBJECT TO SECTION 3.7 AND ARTICLE 9, AND EXCEPT AS OTHERWISE PROVIDED FOR IN THIS AGREEMENT, AEPIMTC CONSULTANT PROVIDES ALL SERVICES WITHOUT ANY EXPRESS OR IMPLIED WARRANTIES, INCLUDING WARRANTIES OF MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE, OR GOOD AND WORKMANLIKE PERFORMANCE. 8
8. LIMITATION OF AEPIMTCS LIABILITY; EXCLUSION OF CONSEQUENTIAL DAMAGES 8.1. Limitation of AEPIMTCs Liability. Except for (a) AEPIMTCs indemnification obligations set forth in Article 9, or (b) the gross negligence of willful misconduct of AEPIMTC or the AEPIMTC Resources, AEPIMTCs aggregate liability, if any, for breach of its obligations under this Agreement related to Services will not exceed the total compensation paid to AEPIMTC for the Services rendered during the Term of this Agreement. 8.2. Exclusion of Consequential Damages. Except for amounts owed to third parties pursuant to indemnification obligations under Section 9 of this Agreement, neither Party will be liable under this Agreement for any special, indirect, incidental, consequential, punitive, or exemplary damages in any action arising out of this Agreement, whether based on contract, tort, or any other theory of liability. 9. INDEMNIFICATION 9.1. Indemnification for Third-Party Claims. 9.1.1. Bellflower shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless AEPIMTC, its Affiliates, and the directors, managers, officers, employees, contractors, consultants and agents of AEPIMTC and its Affiliates (each an AEPIMTC Indemnified Person) for any personal injuries suffered by third parties or damage to a third partys tangible property, including reasonable attorney fees and other documented costs and expenses of defense, and documented costs and expenses of settlement, in each case incurred by the AEPIMTC Indemnified Person, arising in connection with this Agreement, and to the extent such injuries or damage are caused by the negligence, gross negligence or willful misconduct of Bellflower or its officers, employees, agents or subcontractors. 9.1.2. Bellflower shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless AEPIMTC Indemnified Persons against penalties by any Governmental Authority, including NERC, including reasonable attorney fees and other documented costs and expenses of defense, and documented costs and expenses of settlement, in each case incurred by the AEPIMTC Indemnified Person, arising in connection with this Agreement, except to the extent such injuries or damage are caused by the gross negligence or willful misconduct of AEPIMTC or its officers, employees, agents or subcontractors. 9.1.3. AEPIMTC shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless Bellflower, its Affiliates, and its or their directors, managers, officers, employees, and agents (each a Bellflower Indemnified Person) for any personal injuries suffered by third parties or damage to a third partys tangible property, including reasonable attorney fees and other documented costs and expenses of defense, and documented costs and expenses of settlement, in each case incurred by the Bellflower Indemnified Person, arising in connection with the 9
performance by AEPIMTC of its obligations under this Agreement and to the extent such injuries or damage are caused by the negligence, gross negligence or willful misconduct of AEPIMTC or its officers, employees, agents or subcontractors. 9.2. Procedure. Each AEPITMC Indemnified Person or Bellflower Indemnified Person (individually, Indemnified Person), as applicable, must provide prompt notice of any claim for which it seeks indemnity under this provision and cooperate in defense of each such claim. Without the consent of the applicable Indemnified Person, a Party may not settle any such claim for any relief (other than monetary damages) or any claim in the nature of regulatory or similar legal enforcement action by a Governmental Authority. 9.3. Cumulative Rights. The rights and remedies provided to an Indemnified Person under this Article 9 are cumulative with any other right such Person has or may hereafter acquire under Applicable Law and any rights or remedies such Person has may be asserted completely against a Party without regard to any rights or remedies the Indemnified Person may have against any other Person. 10. CONFIDENTIALITY 10.1. Confidential Information. For purposes of this Agreement, a Partys Confidential Information consists of information possessed by that Party which is confidential and commercially valuable and which is specifically identified to the other Party as confidential. Information is Confidential Information only if it is clearly designated or marked in writing as confidential on the face of the document, or, if the information is conveyed orally or by inspection, if the Party providing the information (the Disclosing Party) informs, in writing, the Party receiving the information (the Receiving Party) that the information is confidential. Confidential Information will not include any information which the Receiving Party can demonstrate: (a) has become available to the public through no breach of this Agreement; (b) was previously known by the Receiving Party without any obligation to hold it in confidence; (c) was received on a non-confidential basis from a third party free to disclose such information without restriction; or (d) was independently developed by the Receiving Party without the use of Confidential Information of the Disclosing Party. 10.2. Receipt and Disclosure. For purposes of this Agreement, a Party will be deemed to have received Confidential Information of the other Party if such Confidential Information is by any means disclosed or delivered to the Receiving Party or any of its or its Affiliates equity owners, directors, managers, officers, employees, advisors, attorneys, agents, or prospective or actual lenders or investors (its Representatives). Each Party hereto agrees that it shall hold in strict confidence and shall not disclose or use any Confidential Information belonging to the other Party hereto for the period ending eighteen (18 months after the expiration of the Term or earlier termination of this Agreement. The Receiving Party may disclose Confidential Information to its Representatives for purposes of meeting its obligations and exercising its rights hereunder, provided that the Representatives shall be informed of the confidentiality obligations provided herein. 10
Each Party agrees to be responsible for any breach of the confidentiality obligations under this Agreement by its Representatives. 10.3. Required Disclosures. If a Party is required pursuant to Applicable Law or otherwise becomes legally compelled to disclose any of the Confidential Information or the fact that the Confidential Information has been made available to it, such Party shall (unless prohibited by Applicable Law from doing so) promptly notify the Disclosing Party in order that the Disclosing Party may seek a protective order or such other remedy as the Disclosing Party may consider appropriate in the circumstances. In any event, the compelled Party may disclose only that portion of the Confidential Information which such Party is legally required to disclose in the judgment of the Partys legal counsel without any liability to the Disclosing Party hereunder and such disclosure shall not be a breach of this Article 9.3. 10.4. Return or Destruction. The Receiving Party, upon written request from the Disclosing Party, shall promptly return or destroy all Confidential Information in its possession and the Receiving Party shall destroy its Evaluation Materials. If requested by the Disclosing Party, the Receiving Party shall provide the Disclosing Party with a certification that all Confidential Information and Evaluation Materials have either been returned or destroyed, as applicable. The return or destruction of the Confidential Information shall not extinguish any rights or obligations under this Agreement with respect to the Confidential Information. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the Receiving Party shall not be required to purge any historical backup media and may retain one or more copies of the Confidential Information solely for archival purposes and as required by Applicable Law; provided, however, that the Receiving Party and its Representatives shall continue to keep such information confidential in accordance with the terms of this Agreement, notwithstanding any termination of this Agreement, and no effort to access such stored information shall be made other than for the purpose of any compliance proceedings. 10.5. Survival. The provisions of this Article 9.3 shall survive a termination of this Agreement. 11. GENERAL PROVISIONS 11.1. Notices. Any notice that is required or permitted under this Agreement may be given by personal delivery to the Party entitled thereto, by e-mail (with confirmation of receipt), by any courier service which guarantees overnight, receipted delivery, or by U.S. Certified or Registered Mail, return receipt requested, addressed to the Party entitled thereto, at the following addresses. Notices shall be deemed received upon delivery or tender of delivery to the intended recipient; provided, however, that notice sent by email shall be deemed received when the sender has electronic confirmation that it was sent to all parties (and has retained a confirmation of the delivery). Any Party may change its address or email for notice by written notice to the other Parties in accordance with this Section. Such change will not necessitate a filing under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act.

Nothing in this Agreement, express or implied, is intended to confer upon any third party any rights, remedies, obligations, or liabilities under or by reason of this Agreement, except as expressly provided in this Agreement. In the event of conflict between the ICSA and this Agreement, the terms of this Agreement shall control. 12
11.6. Forbearance and Waiver. Except where a specific time period is provided hereunder for the exercise of a right or remedy, any Partys forbearance in the exercise or enforcement of any right or remedy under this Agreement will not constitute a waiver thereof, and a waiver under one circumstance will not constitute a waiver under any other circumstance. 11.7. Partial Invalidity. Any invalidity, illegality, or unenforceability of any provision of this Agreement in any jurisdiction will not invalidate or render illegal or unenforceable the remaining provisions hereof in such jurisdiction and will not invalidate or render illegal or unenforceable such provision in any other jurisdiction. 11.8. Survival. Any provision specifically designated in this Agreement to survive the termination hereof and (unless otherwise expressly provided) any other provision which, by its nature, necessarily may become performable by a Party after termination of this Agreement will survive termination of this Agreement. 11.9. Governing Law; Venue; Waiver of Jury Trial. 11.9.1. Except as to matters preempted by the Constitution and statutes of the United States of America or regulations promulgated thereunder, this Agreement will be governed by, interpreted, construed, and enforced in accordance with the laws of the State of Indiana without regard to any conflict-of-law provisions that may refer to the laws of any other jurisdiction. After giving effect to the preceding sentence, this Agreement is subject to all valid applicable federal, state, and local laws, ordinances, rules, and regulations of duly constituted regulatory authorities having jurisdiction. 11.9.2. The Parties hereby irrevocably submit to the exclusive jurisdiction of any state or federal court sitting in the State of Indiana any action or proceeding arising out of, or relating to, this Agreement, and irrevocably agree that all claims in respect of such action or proceeding may be heard and determined in any such court. 11.9.3. THE PARTIES EACH HEREBY IRREVOCABLY WAIVE ALL RIGHT TO TRIAL BY JURY IN ANY ACTION, PROCEEDING OR COUNTERCLAIM ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO ANY OF THE TRANSACTIONS CONTEMPLATED HEREBY. EACH PARTY FURTHER WAIVES ANY RIGHT TO CONSOLIDATE ANY ACTION IN WHICH A JURY TRIAL HAS BEEN WAIVED WITH ANY OTHER ACTION IN WHICH A JURY TRIAL CANNOT BE OR HAS NOT BEEN WAIVED. 11.10. Multiple Counterparts. This Agreement may be executed by the Parties in multiple original counterparts, and each such counterpart will constitute an original hereof.

1. Materials
Materials charges are made in four sub-categories: (1) direct material costs (DM), which may be (a) delivered direct from vendors to the job site (VDM), or (b) issued from company stores (SDM); (2) purchasing expenses (PE); (3) stores expenses (SE); and (4) exempt minor materials (EM). The latter three costs are charged using material loading rates described below.
DM costs are vendor invoiced charges for items, other than exempt minor materials, which are used for maintenance. PE are material overhead costs incurred in selecting and ordering materials. SE are the costs of performing the stores function. EM are low cost expendable materials, supplies, and hand tools used in transmission operation and maintenance.
VDM are charged at cost, plus a purchasing loading rate (plr) of 1%, up to a maximum of $150 per invoice. SDM are charged at cost, plus a combined stores/purchasing loading rate (slr) and an EM loading rate (mlr).
Projected annual SE and EM costs are divided by projected annual costs of stores issued materials (SDM + EM) to determine projected SE and EM loading rates. The rates are reviewed monthly and adjusted as required to clear current year SE and EM costs to the accounts charged with the materials issued.
In symbolic format, the charges for materials are calculated as follows:
M = DM + [VDM x (plr), up to $150/bill] + SDM x (1 + (mlr)) x (slr)
2. Labor
Labor is charged to maintenance work orders in three parts - direct labor (DL), fringe labor costs (FL), and miscellaneous out-of-pocket employee expenses (ME). DL charges reflect the actual work hours (whr) and basic hourly rates of pay (hrp) for the personnel that are directly involved; i.e., DL = (whr) x (hrp). FL costs for vacation, holiday, sick leave, and other paid time away, plus payroll taxes, insurance, workers compensation, pension, savings plan expenses, etc. are recovered through labor loading rates (llr) that are developed by dividing FL earned payroll. The llr are reviewed monthly and adjusted, as needed, to clear FL costs yearly.
In symbolic format, the charges for labor are calculated as follows:
L = DL + FL + ME = DL x (1 + llr) + ME
3. Equipment
Equipment (E), primarily vehicles, used in the performance of maintenance are charged based on actual hours of usage (aeu) and hourly equipment cost rates (ecr). Cost of purchasing, leasing, and operating equipment, by equipment class, are collected in clearing accounts and

In symbolic format, E charges are calculated as follows:
E = (aeu) x (ecr)
4. Outside Services
The actual amount of invoices received from vendors for restorative and other maintenance services (S) performed by third parties for AEPIMTC are charged in maintenance billings by AEPIMTC.
5. Engineering and Administration
Engineering and administrative overhead loading rates are used to allocate engineering, supervision, and administrative overhead costs not assigned to specific project work orders. AEPIMTC uses separate loading rates for American Electric Power Service Corporation (AEPSC) engineering (SCEt&d) and construction overhead costs (CCO).
As the description of Construction Overhead Procedure in Section B below shows, the CCO and SCEt&d loading rates (cclr and sclrt&d, respectively) are derived in the normal course of business for the purpose of capturing the portions of AEPSC engineering and operating company construction overhead costs which are incurred in connection with transmission and distribution (T&D) plan construction. The cclr and sclrt&d are reviewed monthly and updated, as needed, to clear the respective engineering and administrative overhead costs yearly.
In symbolic format, the engineering and administration overhead costs (O) are calculated as follows:
O = CCO + SCEt&d
Where CCO = (M + L + E + S) x cclr
and SCEt&d = (M + L + E + S + CCO) x sclrt&d

The charges billed for Maintenance Services in each of the previously identified six categories are discussed in order below.
When invoicing for Maintenance Services, AEP agrees to provide Pioneer reasonably sufficient detail so that the total charges assessed are identified per the six cost categories described below.
1. Materials
Materials charges are made in four sub-categories: (1) direct material costs (DM), which may be (a) delivered direct from vendors to the job site (VDM), or (b) issued from company stores (SDM); (2) purchasing expenses (PE); (3) stores expenses (SE); and (4) exempt minor materials (EM). The latter three costs are charged using material loading rates described below.
DM costs are vendor invoiced charges for items, other than exempt minor materials, which are used for maintenance. PE are material overhead costs incurred in selecting and ordering materials. SE are the costs of performing the stores function. EM are low cost expendable materials, supplies, and hand tools used in transmission operation and maintenance.
VDM are charged at cost, plus a purchasing loading rate (plr) of 1%, up to a maximum of $150 per invoice. SDM are charged at cost, plus a combined stores/purchasing loading rate (slr) and an EM loading rate (mlr).
Projected annual SE and EM costs are divided by projected annual costs of stores issued materials (SDM + EM) to determine projected SE and EM loading rates. The rates are reviewed monthly and adjusted as required to clear current year SE and EM costs to the accounts charged with the materials issued.
In symbolic format, the charges for materials are calculated as follows:
M = DM + [VDM x (plr), up to $150/bill] + SDM x (1 + (mlr)) x (slr)
2. Labor
Labor is charged to maintenance work orders in three parts - direct labor (DL), fringe labor costs (FL), and miscellaneous out-of-pocket employee expenses (ME). DL charges reflect the actual work hours (whr) and basic hourly rates of pay (hrp) for the personnel that are directly involved; i.e., DL = (whr) x (hrp). FL costs (such as vacation, holiday, sick leave, and other paid time away, plus payroll taxes, insurance, workers compensation, pension, and savings plan expenses) are recovered through labor loading rates (llr) that are developed by dividing FL earned payroll. The llr are reviewed monthly and adjusted, as needed, to clear FL costs yearly.
In symbolic format, the charges for labor are calculated as follows:
L = DL + FL + ME = DL x (1 + llr) + ME

3. Equipment
Equipment (E), primarily vehicles, used in the performance of maintenance is charged based on actual hours of usage (aeu) and hourly equipment cost rates (ecr). Costs of purchasing, leasing, and operating equipment, by equipment class, are collected in clearing accounts and divided by total hours of usage by class to develop the E cost rates. E cost rates are reviewed quarterly and adjusted, as needed, to clear the cost of E.
In symbolic format, E charges are calculated as follows:
E = (aeu) x (ecr)
4. Outside Services
The actual amount of invoices received from vendors for restorative and other maintenance services (S) performed by third parties for AEP is charged in maintenance billings by AEP.
5. Engineering and Administration
Engineering and administrative overhead loading rates are used to allocate engineering, supervision, and administrative overhead costs not assigned to specific project work orders. AEP uses separate loading rates for American Electric Power Service Corporation (AEPSC) engineering (SCEt&d) and construction overhead costs (CCO).
As the description of Construction Overhead Procedure in Section 1.B below shows, the CCO and SCEt&d loading rates (cclr and sclrt&d, respectively) are derived in the normal course of business for the purpose of capturing the portions of AEPSC engineering and operating company construction overhead costs which are incurred in connection with transmission and distribution plan construction. The cclr and sclrt&d are reviewed monthly and updated, as needed, to clear the respective engineering and administrative overhead costs yearly.
In symbolic format, the engineering and administration overhead costs (O) are calculated as follows:
O = CCO + SCEt&d
Where CCO = (M + L + E + S) x cclr
and SCEt&d = (M + L + E + S + CCO) x sclrt&d
